__NOTOC__ {{Infobox book | name = Captive Audience | image = Captive Audience.jpg | caption = | author = [[Susan P. Crawford]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = [[Yale University Press]] | pub_date = 2013 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 360 pp. | isbn = 978-0300153132 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Captive Audience: The Telecom Industry and Monopoly Power in the New Gilded Age''''' is an American non-fiction book by the legal expert [[Susan P. Crawford]].<ref name=crawford2013>{{Citation |publisher = Yale University Press |publication-place = New Haven |author = Susan P. Crawford |url = https://openlibrary.org/books/OL25356276M/Captive_audience |title = Captive Audience |publication-date = 2013 }}</ref> It describes high-speed [[internet access]] in the United States as [[Public good|essential]] (like [[electric utility|electricity]]) but currently too [[Internet access#Data rates|slow]] and too [[Internet access#Pricing and spending|expensive]]. To enable widespread [[quality of life]] and to ensure [[Competitiveness#National competitiveness|national competitiveness]] "most Americans should have access to reasonably priced [[Gigabit Ethernet|1-Gb]] symmetric [[fiber-to-the-home]] [[Computer network|networks]]."<ref name=crawford2013 /> Crawford explains why the United States should revise national policy to increase competition in a market currently dominated by [[Comcast]], [[Verizon Communications]], [[AT&T]], and [[Time Warner Cable]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/17/opinion/krugman-barons-of-broadband.html |author=[[Paul Krugman]] |work=New York Times |title=Barons of Broadband |date= February 16, 2014 |accessdate= February 17, 2014 }}</ref> Meanwhile, towns and cities should consider setting up [[Municipal broadband|local networks]] after the example of pioneers such as [[Lafayette, Louisiana#Utilities|Lafayette, Louisiana]]'s [[LUSFiber]] and [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]'s [[EPB]].
==See also== * [[Institute for Local Self-Reliance]] * [[Comcast NBC merger]] * [[Criticism of Comcast]] * [[Federal Communications Commission]] * [[National Broadband Plan (United States)]] * [[Municipal broadband]] * [[Municipal wireless network#Cities with municipal wi-fi|Cities with Municipal Wireless Networks]]
