{{Infobox writer |name = Jean-Gabriel Castel |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1925|06|21}} |birth_place = [[Nice]], [[France]] |death_date = |death_place = | language = [[French language|French]] | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = Canadian | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = }} '''Jean-Gabriel Castel''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|OC|OOnt|QC|FRSC}} (born June 21, 1925) is a [[France|French]] and [[Canadians|Canadian]] law professor and Professor Emeritus at [[Osgoode Hall Law School]]. He currently teaches a course at Osgoode in conflicts of law.
Born in [[Nice]], [[France]] he served in the [[French Resistance]] during [[World War II]] receiving [[military decoration]]s for his service. After the war, he received two law degrees in [[Paris]]. He was one of the first foreign Fulbright scholars. He received a J.D. in 1953 from the [[University of Michigan]] and a D. Juris. in 1958 from [[Harvard University]].
From 1954 to 1959, he taught at the Faculty of Law of [[McGill University]], where he served as the first Faculty Advisor to the ''[[McGill Law Journal]]''.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=''[[McGill Law Journal]]'' |date=1955 |title=Masthead, Volume 1, Issue 4}}</ref> In 1959, he moved to Osgoode Hall Law School and taught there until his retirement in 1999. From 1957 to 1984, he was [[Editing|Editor-in-Chief]] of the [[Canadian Bar Review]].
He is the author of ''Canadian Conflict of Laws'', the leading Canadian work on the conflict of laws.
In 1985, he was made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] in recognition for being "known around the world as an authority on the subject of private international law".<ref>{{OCC|270}}</ref> He is a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]] and a member of the [[Order of Ontario]]. He is a Chevalier de la [[Legion of Honour|Légion d’Honneur]] and officer de l’Ordre national du Mérite.
