{{ Infobox University| |name = The Netherlands Institute for the Law of the Sea |image = |established = 1984 |director = |home = [[Utrecht University]] |city = [[Utrecht]] |country = [[Netherlands]] |website = [http://www.uu.nl/nilos NILOS] {{nl icon}}, [http://www.uu.nl/faculty/leg/nl/organisatie/departementen/departementrechtsgeleerdheid/organisatie/onderdelen/NetherlandsInstitutefortheLawoftheSea/Pages/default.aspx] {{en icon}} |}}
The '''Netherlands Institute for the Law of the Sea''' (NILOS) is a [[research institute]] established at the [[University of Utrecht]].<ref>Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences (KNAW), [http://www.onderzoekinformatie.nl/en/oi/nod/organisatie/ORG1237218/ Netherlands Institute for the Law of the Sea (NILOS)]</ref>
In 1984, it was developed jointly by the Utrecht School of Law and the Centre for Environmental Policy and Law (CELP)/NILOS. The university's Department of Public International, Social and Economic Law (ISEP) was also involved from the outset.<ref name="nilos_overview">NILOS, [http://www.uu.nl/faculty/leg/NL/organisatie/departementen/departementrechtsgeleerdheid/organisatie/onderdelen/NetherlandsInstitutefortheLawoftheSea/Pages/default.aspx Overview]</ref>
The purpose of the institute is: * to develop and sustain expertise on all issues related to the law of the sea;<ref name="nilos_overview"/> * to enhance and broaden awareness and knowledge of the law of the sea;<ref name="nilos_overview"/> * to assist states - in particular developing states -, intergovernmental organizations, national and international non-governmental organizations, companies and individuals in dealing with law of the sea issues.<ref>NILOS, [http://www.uu.nl/faculty/leg/NL/organisatie/departementen/departementrechtsgeleerdheid/organisatie/onderdelen/NetherlandsInstitutefortheLawoftheSea/Pages/research.aspx Research]</ref>
In 2000, NILOS and the [[Sydney Law School|Faculty of Law]] at the [[University of Sydney]] in [[New South Wales, Australia]] initiated a joint research project studying institutional frameworks developed in the 21st century as the law of the sea evolves.<ref>Elferink, Alex G. Oude ''et al.'' (2004). ''Oceans Management in the 21st Century: Institutional Frameworks and Responses,'' p. v.</ref>
==Publications== The institute publishes annual and biennial reports, books. documentary yearbooks, newsletter, online papers.<ref>NILOS, [http://www.uu.nl/faculty/leg/NL/organisatie/departementen/departementrechtsgeleerdheid/organisatie/onderdelen/NetherlandsInstitutefortheLawoftheSea/publications/Pages/default.aspx Publications]</ref>
