{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Sibbach v. Wilson & Co. |ArgueDate=December 17 |ArgueYear=1940 |DecideDate=January 13 |DecideYear=1941 |FullName=Sibbach v. Wilson & Company, Incorporated |USVol=312 |USPage=1 |ParallelCitations=61 S. Ct. 422; 85 [[L. Ed.]] 479; 1941 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 1032 |Prior=108 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/108/415/1477883/ 415] ([[7th Cir.]] 1939); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, {{ussc|309|650|1940|el=no}}. |Holding=In a diversity jurisdiction case, important and substantial procedures are considered "Procedural" not "Substantive" and the [[Federal Rules of Civil Procedure]] apply. |SCOTUS=1940-1941 |Majority=Roberts |JoinMajority=Hughes, McReynolds, Stone, Reed |Dissent=Frankfurter |JoinDissent=Black, Douglas, Murphy |LawsApplied= }} '''''Sibbach v. Wilson & Co.''''', 312 U.S. 1 (1941), was a decision by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] in which the Court held that under [[United States|American]] law important and substantial [[Procedural law|procedures]] are not substantive, rather they are still considered [[Procedural law|procedural]], and federal law applies.
This was a post-''[[Erie Railroad Co. v. Tompkins|Erie]]'' decision, and thus the decision whether to apply the law of the state of jurisdiction or uniform federal rules depended on whether the rule in question was procedural or substantive in nature.
==See also== *[[Erie doctrine]] *[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 312]]
